# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pose-estimation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] In computer vision, **articulated body pose estimation** is the task of algorithmically determining the pose of a body composed of connected parts (joints and rigid parts) from image or video data.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] This challenging problem, central to enabling robots and other systems to understand human actions and interactions, has been a long-standing research area due to the complexity of modeling the relationship between visual observations and pose, as well as the wide range of applications.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Enabling robots to perceive humans in their environment is crucial for effective interaction.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] For example, interpreting pointing gestures requires the ability to recognize and understand human body pose.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] This makes pose estimation a significant and challenging problem in computer vision, driving extensive research and development of numerous algorithms over the past two decades.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Many successful approaches rely on training complex models with large datasets.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Articulated pose estimation is particularly difficult due to the high dimensionality of human movement.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The human body has 244 degrees of freedom and 230 joints.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] While not all joint movements are readily apparent, even a simplified representation of the body with 10 major parts and 20 degrees of freedom presents considerable challenges.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Algorithms must account for substantial appearance variations caused by clothing, body shape, size, and hairstyles.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Ambiguities arise from occlusions, both self-occlusions (e.g., a hand obscuring the face) and occlusions from external objects.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Furthermore, most algorithms operate on monocular (2D) images, which lack inherent 3D information, exacerbating the ambiguity.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Varying lighting conditions and camera viewpoints further complicate the task.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] These difficulties are amplified when real-time performance or other constraints are imposed.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Recent research explores the use of RGB-D cameras, which capture both color and depth information, to address the limitations of monocular approaches.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The typical articulated body pose estimation system involves a model-based approach, in which the pose estimation is achieved by maximizing/minimizing a similarity/dissimilarity between an observation (input) and a template model.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] These sensors produce intermediate representations that are directly used by the model.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The basic idea of part based model can be attributed to the human skeleton.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Any object having the property of articulation can be broken down into smaller parts wherein each part can take different orientations, resulting in different articulations of the same object.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Different scales and orientations of the main object can be articulated to scales and orientations of the corresponding parts.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] To formulate the model so that it can be represented in mathematical terms, the parts are connected to each other using springs.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] As such, the model is also known as a spring model.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The degree of closeness between each part is accounted for by the compression and expansion of the springs.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] There is geometric constraint on the orientation of springs.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] For example, limbs of legs cannot move 360 degrees.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Hence parts cannot have that extreme orientation.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The spring model forms a graph G(V,E) where V (nodes) corresponds to the parts and E (edges) represents springs connecting two neighboring parts.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Each location in the image can be reached by the x and y coordinates of the pixel location.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Then the cost associated in joining the spring between $\mathbf {i} ^{th}$ and the $\mathbf {j} ^{th}$ point can be given by $S(\mathbf {p} _{i},\,\mathbf {p} _{j})=S(\mathbf {p} _{i}-\mathbf {p} _{j})$ .
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The above equation simply represents the spring model used to describe body pose.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] To estimate pose from images, cost or energy function must be minimized.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] This energy function consists of two terms.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The first is related to how each component matches the image data and the second deals with how much the oriented (deformed) parts match, thus accounting for articulation along with object detection.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The part models, also known as pictorial structures, are of one of the basic models on which other efficient models are built by slight modification.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] One such example is the flexible mixture model which reduces the database of hundreds or thousands of deformed parts by exploiting the notion of local rigidity.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The kinematic skeleton is constructed by a tree-structured chain.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] where $R_{l}$ denotes the local transformation from body segment $S_{l}$ to its parent $\operatorname {par} (S_{l})$ .
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Each joint in the body has 3 degrees of freedom (DoF) rotation.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Given a transformation matrix $T_{l}$ , the joint position at the T-pose can be transferred to its corresponding position in the world coordination.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] In many works, the 3D joint rotation is expressed as a normalized quaternion $[x,y,z,w]$ due to its continuity that can facilitate gradient-based optimization in the parameter estimation.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Since about 2016, deep learning has emerged as the dominant method for performing accurate articulated body pose estimation.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Rather than building an explicit model for the parts as above, the appearances of the joints and relationships between the joints of the body are learned from large training sets.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Models generally focus on extracting the 2D positions of joints (keypoints), the 3D positions of joints, or the 3D shape of the body from either a single or multiple images.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The first deep learning models that emerged focused on extracting the 2D positions of human joints in an image.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Such models take in an image and pass it through a convolutional neural network to obtain a series of heatmaps (one for each joint) which take on high values where joints are detected.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] When there are multiple people per image, two main techniques have emerged for grouping joints within each person.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] In the first, "bottom-up" approach, the neural network is trained to also generate "part affinity fields" which indicate the location of limbs.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Using these fields, joints can be grouped limb by limb by solving a series of assignment problems.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] In the second, "top-down" approach, an additional network is used to first detect people in the image and then the pose estimation network is applied to each image.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] With the advent of multiple datasets with human pose annotated in multiple views, models which detect 3D joint positions became more popular.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] These again fell into two categories In the first, a neural network is used to detect 2D joint positions from each view and these detections are then triangulated to obtain 3D joint positions.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The 2D network may be refined to produce better detections based on the 3D data.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Furthermore, such approaches often have filters in both 2D and 3D to refine the detected points.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] In the second, a neural network is trained end-to-end to predict 3D joint positions directly from a set of images, without 2D joint position intermediate detections.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Such approaches often project image features into a cube and then use a 3D convolutional neural network to predict a 3D heatmap for each joint.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Concurrently with the work above, scientists have been working on estimating the full 3D shape of a human or animal from a set of images.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Most of the work is based on estimating the appropriate pose of the skinned multi-person linear (SMPL) model within an image.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Variants of the SMPL model for other animals have also been developed.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Generally, some keypoints and a silhouette are detected for each animal within the image, and then the parameters 3D shape model are fit to match the position of keypoints and silhouette.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] The above algorithms all rely on annotated images, which can be time-consuming to produce.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] To address this issue, computer vision researchers have developed new algorithms which can learn 3D keypoints given only annotated 2D images from a single view or identify keypoints given videos without any annotations.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Personal care robots may be deployed in future assisted living homes.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] For these robots, high-accuracy human detection and pose estimation is necessary to perform a variety of tasks, such as fall detection.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Additionally, this application has a number of performance constraints.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Traditionally, character animation has been a manual process.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] However, poses can be synced directly to a real-life actor through specialized pose estimation systems.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Older systems relied on markers or specialized suits.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Recent advances in pose estimation and motion capture have enabled markerless applications, sometimes in real time.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Car accidents account for about two percent of deaths globally each year.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] As such, an intelligent system tracking driver pose may be useful for emergency alerts .
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Along the same lines, pedestrian detection algorithms have been used successfully in autonomous cars, enabling the car to make smarter decisions.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Commercially, pose estimation has been used in the context of video games, popularized with the Microsoft Kinect sensor (a depth camera).
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] These systems track the user to render their avatar in-game, in addition to performing tasks like gesture recognition to enable the user to interact with the game.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] As such, this application has a strict real-time requirement.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Pose estimation has been used to detect postural issues such as scoliosis by analyzing abnormalities in a patient's posture, physical therapy, and the study of the cognitive brain development of young children by monitoring motor functionality.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] Other applications include video surveillance, animal tracking and behavior understanding, sign language detection, advanced human–computer interaction, and markerless motion capturing.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] A commercially successful but specialized computer vision-based articulated body pose estimation technique is optical motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] This approach involves placing markers on the individual at strategic locations to capture the 6 degrees-of-freedom of each body part.
[src:pose-estimation/articulated-body-pose-estimation] At present, several companies are working on articulated body pose estimation.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:pose-estimation/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:pose-estimation/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In films, television shows and video games, motion capture refers to recording actions of human actors and using that information to animate digital character models in 2D or 3D computer animation.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] When it includes face and fingers or captures subtle expressions or voices, it is often referred to as **performance capture**.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In many fields, motion capture is sometimes called **motion tracking**, but in filmmaking and games, motion tracking usually refers more to match moving.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In motion capture sessions, movements of one or more actors are sampled many times per second.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Whereas early techniques used images from multiple cameras to calculate 3D positions, often the purpose of motion capture is to record only the movements of the actor, not their visual appearance.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This *animation data* is mapped to a 3D model so that the model performs the same actions as the actor.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This process may be contrasted with the older technique of rotoscoping.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Camera movements can also be motion captured so that a virtual camera in the scene will pan, tilt or dolly around the stage driven by a camera operator while the actor is performing.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] At the same time, the motion capture system can capture the camera and props as well as the actor's performance.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This allows the computer-generated characters, images and sets to have the same perspective as the video images from the camera.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] A computer processes the data and displays the movements of the actor, providing the desired camera positions in terms of objects in the set.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Retroactively obtaining camera movement data from the captured footage is known as *match moving* or *camera tracking*.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The first virtual actor animated by motion-capture was produced in 1993 by Didier Pourcel and his team at Gribouille.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] It involved "cloning" the body and face of French comedian Richard Bohringer, and then animating it with still-nascent motion-capture tools.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] There are many applications of motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The most common are for video games, movies, and movement capture, however there is a research application for this technology being used at Purdue University in robotics development.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Video games often use motion capture to animate athletes, martial artists, and other in-game characters.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] As early as 1988, an early form of motion capture was used to animate the 2D player characters of Martech's video game *Vixen* (performed by model Corinne Russell) and Magical Company's 2D arcade fighting game *Last Apostle Puppet Show* (to animate digitized sprites).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Motion capture was later notably used to animate the 3D character models in the Sega Model arcade games *Virtua Fighter* (1993) and *Virtua Fighter 2* (1994).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In mid-1995, developer/publisher Acclaim Entertainment had its own in-house motion capture studio built into its headquarters.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Namco's 1995 arcade game *Soul Edge* used passive optical system markers for motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Motion capture also uses athletes in based-off animated games, such as Naughty Dog's Crash Bandicoot, Insomniac Games' Spyro the Dragon, and Rare's Dinosaur Planet.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Indoor positioning is another application for optical motion capture systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Robotics researchers often use motion capture systems when developing and evaluating control, estimation, and perception algorithms and hardware.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In outdoor spaces, it's possible to achieve accuracy to the centimeter by using the Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) together with Real-Time Kinematics (RTK).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] However, this reduces significantly when there is no line-of-sight to the satellites — such as in indoor environments.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The majority of vendors selling commercial optical motion capture systems provide accessible open source drivers that integrate with the popular Robotic Operating System (ROS) framework, allowing researchers and developers to effectively test their robots during development.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In the field of aerial robotics research, motion capture systems are widely used for positioning as well.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Regulations on airspace usage limit how feasible outdoor experiments can be conducted with Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Indoor tests can circumvent such restrictions.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Many labs and institutions around the world have built indoor motion capture volumes for this purpose.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Purdue University houses the world's largest indoor motion capture system, inside the Purdue UAS Research and Test (PURT) facility.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] PURT is dedicated to UAS research, and provides tracking volume of 600,000 cubic feet using 60 motion capture cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The optical motion capture system is able to track targets in its volume with millimeter accuracy, effectively providing the true position of targets — the "ground truth" baseline in research and development.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Results derived from other sensors and algorithms can then be compared to the ground truth data to evaluate their performance.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Movies use motion capture for CGI effects, in some cases replacing traditional cel animation, and for completely CGI creatures, such as Gollum, The Mummy, King Kong, Davy Jones from *Pirates of the Caribbean*, the Na'vi from the film *Avatar*, and Clu from *Tron: Legacy*.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The Great Goblin, the three Stone-trolls, many of the orcs and goblins in the 2012 film *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*, and Smaug were created using motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In the 1990 movie *Total Recall*, the sequence where Arnold Schwarzenegger and other actors walk through an X-ray machine was shot using motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The film *Batman Forever* (1995) used some motion capture for certain visual effects.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Warner Bros. had acquired motion capture technology from arcade video game company Acclaim Entertainment for use in the film's production.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Acclaim's 1995 video game of the same name also used the same motion capture technology to animate the digitized sprite graphics.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The 1999 film *Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace* was the first feature-length film to include a main character created (Jar Jar Binks, played by Ahmed Best), using motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The 2000 Indian-American film *Sinbad: Beyond the Veil of Mists* was the first feature-length film made primarily with motion capture, although many character animators also worked on the film, which had a very limited release.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] 2001's *Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within* was the first widely released movie to be made with motion capture technology.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Despite its poor box-office intake, supporters of motion capture technology took notice.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Storymind Entertainment, which is an independent Ukrainian studio, created a neo-noir third-person / shooter video game called *My Eyes On You*, using motion capture in order to animate its main character, Jordan Adalien, and along with non-playable characters.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Of the three nominees for the 2006 Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, two of the nominees (*Monster House* and the winner *Happy Feet*) used motion capture, and only Disney**·**Pixar's *Cars* was animated without it.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Since 2001, motion capture has been used extensively to simulate or approximate the look of live-action theater, with nearly photorealistic digital character models.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] *The Polar Express* used motion capture to allow Tom Hanks to perform as several distinct digital characters (in which he also provided the voices).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The 2007 adaptation of the saga *Beowulf* animated digital characters whose appearances were based in part on the actors who provided their motions and voices.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] James Cameron's highly popular *Avatar* used this technique to create the Na'vi that inhabit Pandora.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The Walt Disney Company has produced Robert Zemeckis's *A Christmas Carol* using this technique.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In 2007, Disney acquired Zemeckis' ImageMovers Digital (that produces motion capture films), but then closed it in 2011, after a box office failure of *Mars Needs Moms*.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Television series produced entirely with motion capture animation include *Laflaque* in Canada, *Sprookjesboom* and *Cafe de Wereld* in The Netherlands, and *Headcases* in the UK.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Virtual reality and augmented reality providers, such as uSens and Gestigon, allow users to interact with digital content in real time by capturing hand motions.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This can be useful for training simulations, visual perception tests, or performing virtual walk-throughs in a 3D environment.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Motion capture technology is frequently used in digital puppetry systems to drive computer-generated characters in real time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Gait analysis is one application of motion capture in clinical medicine.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Techniques allow clinicians to evaluate human motion across several biomechanical factors, often while streaming this information live into analytical software.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] One innovative use is pose detection, which can empower patients during post-surgical recovery or rehabilitation after injuries.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This approach enables continuous monitoring, real-time guidance, and individually tailored programs to enhance patient outcomes.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Some physical therapy clinics utilize motion capture as an objective way to quantify patient progress.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This method allowed views and angles not possible from a pre-rendered animation.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Cameron was so proud of his results that he invited Steven Spielberg and George Lucas on set to view the system in action.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In Marvel's *The Avengers*, Mark Ruffalo used motion capture so he could play his character the Hulk, rather than have him be only CGI as in previous films, making Ruffalo the first actor to play both the human and the Hulk versions of Bruce Banner.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] FaceRig software uses facial recognition technology from ULSee.Inc to map a player's facial expressions and the body tracking technology from Perception Neuron to map the body movement onto a 2D or 3D character's motion on-screen.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] During *Game Developers Conference* 2016 in San Francisco *Epic Games* demonstrated full-body motion capture live in Unreal Engine.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The whole scene, from the upcoming game *Hellblade* about a woman warrior named Senua, was rendered in real-time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The keynote was a collaboration between *Unreal Engine*, *Ninja Theory*, *3Lateral*, *Cubic Motion*, *IKinema* and *Xsens*.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In 2020, the two-time Olympic figure skating champion Yuzuru Hanyu graduated from Waseda University.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In his thesis, using data provided by 31 sensors placed on his body, he analysed his jumps.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] He evaluated the use of technology both in order to improve the scoring system and to help skaters improve their jumping technique.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In March 2021 a summary of the thesis was published in the academic journal.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Motion tracking or motion capture started as a photogrammetric analysis tool in biomechanics research in the 1970s and 1980s, and expanded into education, training, sports and recently computer animation for television, cinema, and video games as the technology matured.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Since the 20th century, the performer has to wear markers near each joint to identify the motion by the positions or angles between the markers.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Acoustic, inertial, LED, magnetic or reflective markers, or combinations of any of these, are tracked, optimally at least two times the frequency rate of the desired motion.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The resolution of the system is important in both the spatial resolution and temporal resolution as motion blur causes almost the same problems as low resolution.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Since the beginning of the 21st century - and because of the rapid growth of technology - new methods have been developed.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Most modern systems can extract the silhouette of the performer from the background.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Afterwards all joint angles are calculated by fitting in a mathematical model into the silhouette.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] For movements you can not see a change of the silhouette, there are hybrid systems available that can do both (marker and silhouette), but with less marker.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In robotics, some motion capture systems are based on simultaneous localization and mapping.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The centroid of the marker is estimated as a position within the two-dimensional image that is captured.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The grayscale value of each pixel can be used to provide sub-pixel accuracy by finding the centroid of the Gaussian.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] An object with markers attached at known positions is used to calibrate the cameras and obtain their positions, and the lens distortion of each camera is measured.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] If two calibrated cameras see a marker, a three-dimensional fix can be obtained.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Typically a system will consist of around 2 to 48 cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Systems of over three hundred cameras exist to try to reduce marker swap.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Extra cameras are required for full coverage around the capture subject and multiple subjects.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Vendors have constraint software to reduce the problem of marker swapping since all passive markers appear identical.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Unlike active marker systems and magnetic systems, passive systems do not require the user to wear wires or electronic equipment.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Instead, hundreds of rubber balls are attached with reflective tape, which needs to be replaced periodically.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The markers are usually attached directly to the skin (as in biomechanics), or they are velcroed to a performer wearing a full-body spandex/lycra suit designed specifically for motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This type of system can capture large numbers of markers at frame rates usually around 120 to 160 fps although by lowering the resolution and tracking a smaller region of interest they can track as high as 10,000 fps.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Active optical systems triangulate positions by illuminating one LED at a time very quickly or multiple LEDs with software to identify them by their relative positions, somewhat akin to celestial navigation.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Rather than reflecting light back that is generated externally, the markers themselves are powered to emit their own light.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Since the inverse square law provides one quarter of the power at two times the distance, this can increase the distances and volume for capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This also enables a high signal-to-noise ratio, resulting in very low marker jitter and a resulting high measurement resolution (often down to 0.1 mm within the calibrated volume).
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The TV series *Stargate SG1* produced episodes using an active optical system for the VFX allowing the actor to walk around props that would make motion capture difficult for other non-active optical systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] ILM used active markers in *Van Helsing* to allow capture of Dracula's flying brides on very large sets similar to Weta's use of active markers in *Rise of the Planet of the Apes*.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The power to each marker can be provided sequentially in phase with the capture system providing a unique identification of each marker for a given capture frame at a cost to the resultant frame rate.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The ability to identify each marker in this manner is useful in real-time applications.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The alternative method of identifying markers is to do it algorithmically requiring extra processing of the data.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] There are also possibilities to find the position by using colored LED markers.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In these systems, each color is assigned to a specific point of the body.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] One of the earliest active marker systems in the 1980s was a hybrid passive-active mocap system with rotating mirrors and colored glass reflective markers and which used masked linear array detectors.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Active marker systems can further be refined by strobing one marker on at a time, or tracking multiple markers over time and modulating the amplitude or pulse width to provide marker ID.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] 12-megapixel spatial resolution modulated systems show more subtle movements than 4-megapixel optical systems by having both higher spatial and temporal resolution.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Directors can see the actor's performance in real-time, and watch the results on the motion capture-driven CG character.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The unique marker IDs reduce the turnaround, by eliminating marker swapping and providing much cleaner data than other technologies.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] LEDs with onboard processing and radio synchronization allow motion capture outdoors in direct sunlight while capturing at 120 to 960 frames per second due to a high-speed electronic shutter.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Computer processing of modulated IDs allows less hand cleanup or filtered results for lower operational costs.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This higher accuracy and resolution requires more processing than passive technologies, but the additional processing is done at the camera to improve resolution via subpixel or centroid processing, providing both high resolution and high speed.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These motion capture systems typically cost $20,000 for an eight-camera, 12-megapixel spatial resolution 120-hertz system with one actor.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] One can reverse the traditional approach based on high-speed cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Systems such as Prakash use inexpensive multi-LED high-speed projectors.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The specially built multi-LED IR projectors optically encode the space.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Instead of retro-reflective or active light emitting diode (LED) markers, the system uses photosensitive marker tags to decode the optical signals.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] By attaching tags with photo sensors to scene points, the tags can compute not only their own locations of each point, but also their own orientation, incident illumination, and reflectance.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These tracking tags work in natural lighting conditions and can be imperceptibly embedded in attire or other objects.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The system supports an unlimited number of tags in a scene, with each tag uniquely identified to eliminate marker reacquisition issues.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Since the system eliminates a high-speed camera and the corresponding high-speed image stream, it requires significantly lower data bandwidth.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The tags also provide incident illumination data which can be used to match scene lighting when inserting synthetic elements.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The technique appears ideal for on-set motion capture or real-time broadcasting of virtual sets but has yet to be proven.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Motion capture technology has been available for researchers and scientists for a few decades, which has given new insight into many fields.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The vital part of the system, the underwater camera, has a waterproof housing.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The housing has a finish that withstands corrosion and chlorine which makes it perfect for use in basins and swimming pools.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Industrial high-speed cameras can also be used as infrared cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Infrared underwater cameras come with a cyan light strobe instead of the typical IR light for minimum fall-off underwater and high-speed cameras with an LED light or with the option of using image processing.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] An underwater camera is typically able to measure 15–20 meters depending on the water quality, the camera and the type of marker used.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Unsurprisingly, the best range is achieved when the water is clear, and like always, the measurement volume is also dependent on the number of cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] A range of underwater markers are available for different circumstances.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Different pools require different mountings and fixtures.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Therefore, all underwater motion capture systems are uniquely tailored to suit each specific pool instalment.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] For cameras placed in the center of the pool, specially designed tripods, using suction cups, are provided.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Emerging techniques and research in computer vision are leading to the rapid development of the markerless approach to motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Markerless systems such as those developed at Stanford University, the University of Maryland, MIT, and the Max Planck Institute, do not require subjects to wear special equipment for tracking.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Special computer algorithms are designed to allow the system to analyze multiple streams of optical input and identify human forms, breaking them down into constituent parts for tracking.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Traditionally markerless optical motion tracking is used to keep track of various objects, including airplanes, launch vehicles, missiles and satellites.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Many such optical motion tracking applications occur outdoors, requiring differing lens and camera configurations.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] High-resolution images of the target being tracked can thereby provide more information than just motion data.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The image obtained from NASA's long-range tracking system on the space shuttle Challenger's fatal launch provided crucial evidence about the cause of the accident.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Optical tracking systems are also used to identify known spacecraft and space debris despite the fact that it has a disadvantage compared to radar in that the objects must be reflecting or emitting sufficient light.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] An optical tracking system typically consists of three subsystems: the optical imaging system, the mechanical tracking platform and the tracking computer.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The optical imaging system is responsible for converting the light from the target area into a digital image that the tracking computer can process.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Depending on the design of the optical tracking system, the optical imaging system can vary from as simple as a standard digital camera to as specialized as an astronomical telescope on the top of a mountain.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The specification of the optical imaging system determines the upper limit of the effective range of the tracking system.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The mechanical tracking platform holds the optical imaging system and is responsible for manipulating the optical imaging system in such a way that it always points to the target being tracked.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The dynamics of the mechanical tracking platform combined with the optical imaging system determines the tracking system's ability to keep the lock on a target that changes speed rapidly.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The tracking computer is responsible for capturing the images from the optical imaging system, analyzing the image to extract the target position and controlling the mechanical tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] First, the tracking computer has to be able to capture the image at a relatively high frame rate.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This posts a requirement on the bandwidth of the image-capturing hardware.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The second challenge is that the image processing software has to be able to extract the target image from its background and calculate its position.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Several textbook image-processing algorithms are designed for this task.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This problem can be simplified if the tracking system can expect certain characteristics that is common in all the targets it will track.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The next problem down the line is controlling the tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This is a typical control system design problem rather than a challenge, which involves modeling the system dynamics and designing controllers to control it.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This will however become a challenge if the tracking platform the system has to work with is not designed for real-time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The software that runs such systems is also customized for the corresponding hardware components.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] One example of such software is OpticTracker, which controls computerized telescopes to track moving objects at great distances, such as planes and satellites.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Another option is the software SimiShape, which can also be used hybrid in combination with markers.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] RGB-D cameras such as Kinect capture both the color and depth images.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] By fusing the two images, 3D colored voxels can be captured, allowing motion capture of 3D human motion and human surface in real-time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Because of the use of a single-view camera, motions captured are usually noisy.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Machine learning techniques have been proposed to automatically reconstruct such noisy motions into higher quality ones, using methods such as lazy learning and Gaussian models.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Such method generates accurate enough motion for serious applications like ergonomic assessment.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture technology is based on miniature inertial sensors, biomechanical models and sensor fusion algorithms.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The motion data of the inertial sensors (inertial guidance system) is often transmitted wirelessly to a computer, where the motion is recorded or viewed.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Most inertial systems use inertial measurement units (IMUs) containing a combination of gyroscope, magnetometer, and accelerometer, to measure rotational rates.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These rotations are translated to a skeleton in the software.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Much like optical markers, the more IMU sensors the more natural the data.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] No external cameras, emitters or markers are needed for relative motions, although they are required to give the absolute position of the user if desired.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture systems capture the full six degrees of freedom body motion of a human in real-time and can give limited direction information if they include a magnetic bearing sensor, although these are much lower resolution and susceptible to electromagnetic noise.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Benefits of using Inertial systems include: capturing in a variety of environments including tight spaces, no solving, portability, and large capture areas.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Disadvantages include lower positional accuracy and positional drift which can compound over time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These systems are similar to the Wii controllers but are more sensitive and have greater resolution and update rates.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] They can accurately measure the direction to the ground to within a degree.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The popularity of inertial systems is rising amongst game developers, mainly because of the quick and easy setup resulting in a fast pipeline.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] A range of suits are now available from various manufacturers and base prices range from $1000 to US$80,000.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems directly track body joint angles and are often referred to as exoskeleton motion capture systems, due to the way the sensors are attached to the body.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] A performer attaches the skeletal-like structure to their body and as they move so do the articulated mechanical parts, measuring the performer's relative motion.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems are real-time, relatively low-cost, free from occlusion, and wireless (untethered) systems that have unlimited capture volume.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Typically, they are rigid structures of jointed, straight metal or plastic rods linked together with potentiometers that articulate at the joints of the body.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These suits tend to be in the $25,000 to $75,000 range plus an external absolute positioning system.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Some suits provide limited force feedback or haptic input.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Magnetic systems calculate position and orientation by the relative magnetic flux of three orthogonal coils on both the transmitter and each receiver.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The relative intensity of the voltage or current of the three coils allows these systems to calculate both range and orientation by meticulously mapping the tracking volume.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The sensor output is six degrees of freedom (6DOF), which provides useful results obtained with two-thirds the number of markers required in optical systems; one on upper arm and one on lower arm for elbow position and angle.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The markers are vulnerable to magnetic and electrical interference from metal objects in the environment, like rebar (steel reinforcing bars in concrete) or wiring, which affect the magnetic field, and electrical sources such as monitors, lights, cables and computers.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The sensor response is nonlinear, especially toward edges of the capture area.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The wiring from the sensors tends to preclude extreme performance movements.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] With magnetic systems, it is possible to monitor the results of a motion capture session in real time.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The capture volumes for magnetic systems are dramatically smaller than they are for optical systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] With the magnetic systems, there is a distinction between alternating-current (AC) and direct-current (DC) systems: DC system uses square pulses, AC systems use sine waves.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are flexible parallel plate capacitors that measure either stretch, bend, shear, or pressure and are typically produced from silicone.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] When the sensor stretches or squeezes its capacitance value changes.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] This data can be transmitted via Bluetooth or direct input and used to detect minute changes in body motion.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are unaffected by magnetic interference and are free from occlusion.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The stretchable nature of the sensors also means they do not suffer from positional drift, which is common with inertial systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Stretchable sensors, on the other hands, due to the material properties of their substrates and conducting materials, suffer from relatively low signal-to-noise ratio, requiring filtering or machine learning to make them usable for motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These solutions result in higher latency when compared to alternative sensors.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Most traditional motion capture hardware vendors provide for some type of low-resolution facial capture utilizing anywhere from 32 to 300 markers with either an active or passive marker system.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] All of these solutions are limited by the time it takes to apply the markers, calibrate the positions and process the data.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Ultimately the technology also limits their resolution and raw output quality levels.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] High-fidelity facial motion capture, also known as **performance capture**, is the next generation of fidelity and is utilized to record the more complex movements in a human face in order to capture higher degrees of emotion.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Facial capture is currently arranging itself in several distinct camps, including traditional motion capture data, blend-shaped based solutions, capturing the actual topology of an actor's face, and proprietary systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] These techniques tend to be only limited in feature resolution by the camera resolution, apparent object size and number of cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] If the user's face is 50 percent of the working area of the camera and a camera has megapixel resolution, then sub millimeter facial motions can be detected by comparing frames.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Recent work is focusing on increasing the frame rates and doing optical flow to allow the motions to be retargeted to other computer generated faces, rather than just making a 3D Mesh of the actor and their expressions.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Radio frequency positioning systems are becoming more viable as higher frequency radio frequency devices allow greater precision than older technologies such as radar.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The speed of light is 30 centimeters per nanosecond (billionth of a second), so a 10 gigahertz (billion cycles per second) radio frequency signal enables an accuracy of about 3 centimeters.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] By measuring amplitude to a quarter wavelength, it is possible to improve the resolution down to about 8 mm.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] To achieve the resolution of optical systems, frequencies of 50 gigahertz or higher are needed, which are almost as dependent on line of sight and as easy to block as optical systems.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Multipath and reradiation of the signal are likely to cause additional problems, but these technologies will be ideal for tracking larger volumes with reasonable accuracy, since the required resolution at 100 meter distances is not likely to be as high.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Many scientists believe that radio frequency will never produce the accuracy required for motion capture.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Researchers at Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers said in 2015 that they had made a system that tracks motion by radio frequency signals.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] An alternative approach was developed where the actor is given an unlimited walking area through the use of a rotating sphere, similar to a hamster ball, which contains internal sensors recording the angular movements, removing the need for external cameras and other equipment.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Even though this technology could potentially lead to much lower costs for motion capture, the basic sphere is only capable of recording a single continuous direction.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Additional sensors worn on the person would be needed to record anything more.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Another alternative is using a 6DOF (Degrees of freedom) motion platform with an integrated omni-directional treadmill with high resolution optical motion capture to achieve the same effect.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] The captured person can walk in an unlimited area, negotiating different uneven terrains.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] Applications include medical rehabilitation for balance training, bio-mechanical research and virtual reality.
[src:pose-estimation/motion-capture] In 3D pose estimation, an actor's pose can be reconstructed from an image or depth map.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] In the fields of computing and computer vision, **pose** (or **spatial pose**) represents the position and the orientation of an object, each usually in three dimensions.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Poses are often stored internally as transformation matrices.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] The term “pose” is largely synonymous with the term “transform”, but a transform may often include scale, whereas pose does not.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] In computer vision, the pose of an object is often estimated from camera input by the process of *pose estimation*.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] This information can then be used, for example, to allow a robot to manipulate an object or to avoid moving into the object based on its perceived position and orientation in the environment.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Other applications include skeletal action recognition.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] The specific task of determining the pose of an object in an image (or stereo images, image sequence) is referred to as *pose estimation*.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Pose estimation problems can be solved in different ways depending on the image sensor configuration, and choice of methodology.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Camera resectioning is the process of estimating the parameters of a pinhole camera model approximating the camera that produced a given photograph or video; it determines which incoming light ray is associated with each pixel on the resulting image.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Basically, the process determines the pose of the pinhole camera.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Usually, the camera parameters are represented in a 3 × 4 projection matrix called the *camera matrix*.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] The extrinsic parameters define the camera *pose* (position and orientation) while the intrinsic parameters specify the camera image format (focal length, pixel size, and image origin).
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] This process is often called geometric camera calibration or simply camera calibration, although that term may also refer to photometric camera calibration or be restricted for the estimation of the intrinsic parameters only.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Exterior orientation and interior orientation refer to the determination of only the extrinsic and intrinsic parameters, respectively.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] The classic camera calibration requires special objects in the scene, which is not required in *camera auto-calibration*.
[src:pose-estimation/pose-computer-vision] Camera resectioning is often used in the application of stereo vision where the camera projection matrices of two cameras are used to calculate the 3D world coordinates of a point viewed by both cameras.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Humans perceive a great deal of information about the three-dimensional structure in their environment by moving around it.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] When the observer moves, objects around them move different amounts depending on their distance from the observer.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] This is known as motion parallax, and this depth information can be used to generate an accurate 3D representation of the world around them.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Finding structure from motion presents a similar problem to finding structure from stereo vision.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] In both instances, the correspondence between images and the reconstruction of 3D object needs to be found.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] To find correspondence between images, features such as corner points (edges with gradients in multiple directions) are tracked from one image to the next.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] One of the most widely used feature detectors is the scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT).
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] It uses the maxima from a difference-of-Gaussians (DOG) pyramid as features.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The first step in SIFT is finding a dominant gradient direction.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] To make it rotation-invariant, the descriptor is rotated to fit this orientation.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Another common feature detector is the SURF (*speeded-up robust features*).
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] In SURF, the DOG is replaced with a Hessian matrix-based blob detector.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Also, instead of evaluating the gradient histograms, SURF computes for the sums of gradient components and the sums of their absolute values.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Its usage of integral images allows the features to be detected extremely quickly with high detection rate.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Therefore, comparing to SIFT, SURF is a faster feature detector with drawback of less accuracy in feature positions.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Another type of feature recently made practical for structure from motion are general curves (e.g., locally an edge with gradients in one direction), part of a technology known as *pointless SfM*, useful when point features are insufficient, common in man-made environments.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The features detected from all the images will then be matched.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] One of the matching algorithms that track features from one image to another is the Lucas–Kanade tracker.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Sometimes some of the matched features are incorrectly matched.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] This is why the matches should also be filtered.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] RANSAC (random sample consensus) is the algorithm that is usually used to remove the outlier correspondences.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] In the paper of Fischler and Bolles, RANSAC is used to solve the *location determination problem* (LDP), where the objective is to determine the points in space that project onto an image into a set of landmarks with known locations.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The feature trajectories over time are then used to reconstruct their 3D positions and the camera's motion.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] An alternative is given by so-called direct approaches, where geometric information (3D structure and camera motion) is directly estimated from the images, without intermediate abstraction to features or corners.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] There are several approaches to structure from motion.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] In incremental SfM, camera poses are solved for and added one by one to the collection.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] In global SfM, the poses of all cameras are solved for at the same time.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] A somewhat intermediate approach is out-of-core SfM, where several partial reconstructions are computed that are then integrated into a global solution.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure-from-motion photogrammetry with multi-view stereo provides hyperscale landform models using images acquired from a range of digital cameras and optionally a network of ground control points.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique is not limited in temporal frequency and can provide point cloud data comparable in density and accuracy to those generated by terrestrial and airborne laser scanning at a fraction of the cost.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion is also useful in remote or rugged environments where terrestrial laser scanning is limited by equipment portability and airborne laser scanning is limited by terrain roughness causing loss of data and image foreshortening.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique has been applied in many settings such as rivers, badlands, sandy coastlines, fault zones, landslides, and coral reef settings.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] A full range of digital cameras can be utilized, including digital SLR's, compact digital cameras and even smart phones.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Generally though, higher accuracy data will be achieved with more expensive cameras, which include lenses of higher optical quality.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The technique therefore offers exciting opportunities to characterize surface topography in unprecedented detail and, with multi-temporal data, to detect elevation, position and volumetric changes that are symptomatic of earth surface processes.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Structure from motion can be placed in the context of other digital surveying methods.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Cultural heritage is present everywhere.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Its structural control, documentation and conservation is one of humanity's main duties (UNESCO).
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Under this point of view, SfM is used in order to properly estimate situations as well as planning and maintenance efforts and costs, control and restoration.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The use is accurate as only qualitative considerations are needed.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] It is fast enough to respond to the monument's immediate management needs.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] The first operational phase is an accurate preparation of the photogrammetric surveying where is established the relation between best distance from the object, focal length, the ground sampling distance (GSD) and the sensor's resolution.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] With this information the programmed photographic acquisitions must be made using vertical overlapping of at least 60%.
[src:pose-estimation/structure-from-motion] Furthermore, structure-from-motion photogrammetry represents a non-invasive, highly flexible and low-cost methodology to digitalize historical documents.
